# load library and data
library(tidyverse)
library(knitr)
library(kableExtra)


# load inplate mapping data
tag_plate <- read.csv("Plate_mapping_october2020/PlateMappingReads.csv", header = TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

# Correct one of the tag , as it was written in small letter 
tag_plate$up_constant <- gsub("BSup2","BSUp2", tag_plate$up_constant)

The goal here is to find the best 20-bp-random-barcode (rb20) associated with each pair of ups and downs in-plate tag. There are cases, where the same rb20 is associated with multiple pairs of inline tags. In such cases, we are likely to associated the same rb20 with multiple inline barcode. So, rather than searching the best rb20 by in-line tag, what we can do is: first find the all the pairs of tags associated with a rb20, then count which pairs has the highest number of reads (best-pairs). In doing so, once the rb20 is assigned to the best-pairs, then the same rb20 cannot be assigned to any other tag pairs.

# group by tags and rb20, and select one with read count > 5000, so that we can plot it as image.
cutseqcount <- tag_plate %>%
  group_by(cutseq,up_constant,down_constant) %>%
  tally() %>%
  arrange(desc(n)) %>%
  mutate(ups_downs = paste0(up_constant,"_",down_constant)) %>%
  filter(n > 5000)
# Stacked barplot with multiple groups
ggplot(data=cutseqcount, aes(x=cutseq, y=n, fill=ups_downs)) +
  geom_bar(position="stack", stat="identity")+
  theme_minimal()+
  theme(legend.position="none")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1, size = 7))+
  theme(plot.margin=unit(c(0,0,0,0),"cm"))

Note: Some of the tag is associated with multiple in-line tags, at quite high number of reads.

Select tag with highest read count i.e.CGCCTTTTTGGATGGCGGGC with read counts of 178530. This accounts for ~ 10% of the total reads.

higest_tag <- tag_plate %>%
  filter (cutseq =="CGCCTTTTTGGATGGCGGGC") %>%
  group_by(cutseq,up_constant,down_constant) %>%
  tally() %>%
  arrange(desc(n)) %>%
  mutate(per_on_onetagPair = n/178530 *100) %>%
   mutate(per_on_entireLibrary = n/ 1860004 *100) %>%
  mutate(ups_downs = paste0(up_constant,"_",down_constant)) %>%
  filter(n > 500)

BSUp3_BSDn19_rc pair has the highest number of read counts for rb20: CGCCTTTTTGGATGGCGGGC, which is about ~7% of the reads observed for CGCCTTTTTGGATGGCGGGC or 0.656 % of the entire library.

# Stacked barplot with multiple groups
ggplot(data=higest_tag, aes(x=reorder(ups_downs, -n), y=n, fill=ups_downs)) +
  geom_bar(position="dodge", stat="identity") +

Here, BSUp3_BSDn19_rc is the tag pair with the highest read count. Thus, CGCCTTTTTGGATGGCGGGC get associated with BSUp3_BSDn19_rc. In the case of second highest i.e.BSUp2_BSDn19_rc, the read count is 6598. Note,that with this approach of assigning a rb20 to only one tag-pairs, there is possibility of any other rb20 with count less than that of CGCCTTTTTGGATGGCGGGC (6598) assigned to BSUp3_BSDn19_rc.

We will convert the best_df to two matrix: one for count and another for rb20. Rows represents ups-tag and column represents downs-tag.

# create vector to repsents row and column, with ups and downs tag
ups <-paste0("BSUp",1:16)
downs <- paste0("BSDn",1:24,"_rc")

# create an empty matrix and convert to dataframe with row and column name. This one for saving count.
Mcount <- data.frame(matrix(ncol = length(downs), nrow = length(ups)))
colnames(Mcount) <- downs
rownames(Mcount) <- ups

# create an empty matrix and convert to dataframe with row and column name. This one for saving count normalized by total reads in the library i.e. 1860004 
Mcount_outof_TotalLibrary <- data.frame(matrix(ncol = length(downs), nrow = length(ups)))
colnames(Mcount_outof_TotalLibrary) <- downs
rownames(Mcount_outof_TotalLibrary) <- ups


# create an empty matrix and convert to dataframe with row and column name. This one for saving count, normalized by the reads observed for each unique barcode
Mcount_outof_cutseqCount <- data.frame(matrix(ncol = length(downs), nrow = length(ups)))
colnames(Mcount_outof_cutseqCount) <- downs
rownames(Mcount_outof_cutseqCount) <- ups

# create an empty matrix and convert to dataframe with row and column name. This one for saving rb20.
Mrb <- data.frame(matrix(ncol = length(downs), nrow = length(ups)))
colnames(Mrb) <- downs
rownames(Mrb) <- ups

# create an empty matrix and convert to dataframe with row and column name. This one for saving count, normalized by the reads observed for each unique barcode
BarCount <- data.frame(matrix(ncol = length(downs), nrow = length(ups)))
colnames(BarCount) <- downs
rownames(BarCount) <- ups


# create an empty matrix and convert to dataframe with row and column name. This one for saving count, normalized by the reads observed for each unique barcode
MBarcode <- data.frame(matrix(ncol = length(downs), nrow = length(ups)))
colnames(MBarcode ) <- downs
rownames(MBarcode ) <- ups


# for each tag-paris find the best cutseq 
for (r in 1:length(ups)){
  rc <- ups[r]
  for (col in 1:length(downs)){
    cc <- downs[col]
    getind <- best_df %>% filter(ups==rc & down == cc)
    if (dim(getind)[1]< 1){
      Mcount[r,col] <- NA
      Mrb[r,col] <- NA
    }else{
      max_one <- getind %>% arrange(desc(count)) 
      max_one_row <-  max_one[1, ]
      Mcount[r,col] <-  max_one_row$count
      getcutseq <- as.character(max_one_row$cutseq)
      Mrb[r,col] <- getcutseq
      Mcount_outof_TotalLibrary[r,col] <- max_one_row$count / 1860004  * 100
      get_count_for_cutseq <- cutseq_count %>% filter(cutseq==getcutseq) %>% pull(n)
      Mcount_outof_cutseqCount[r,col] <- max_one_row$count / get_count_for_cutseq  * 100
      
      # find matching getcutseq in barcode mapping in barcode_cutseq_count
      aa = barcode_cutseq_count %>%
        filter(barcode == getcutseq)
      if (dim(aa)[1]< 1){
      BarCount[r,col] <- NA
      MBarcode[r,col] <- NA
    }else{
      BarCount[r,col] <- aa$n
      MBarcode[r,col] <- as.character(aa$barcode)
      }
    } 
  }
}
